3.2 Data Structure
The SC13 base data set contains four fleets:

N_Chile;
SC_Chile_PS;
FarNorth;
Offshore_Trawl.

The composition data structure differs by fleet. Age compositions are used for N_Chile, SC_Chile_PS, and Offshore_Trawl, while the FarNorth fleet is fitted to length compositions through the modelled growth relationship. The file input/1.14.dat indicates that age-composition observations extend from 1980-2025 for the Chilean fleets and 2015-2025 for the offshore fleet, while length-composition observations are available for the Far North fleet from 1980-2025.
The same data file also includes seven abundance indices:

Chile_AcousCS;
Chile_AcousN;
Chile_CPUE;
DEPM;
Peru_Acoustic;
Peru_CPUE;
Offshore_CPUE.

This is therefore not a sparse index-only assessment. It is a fully integrated model in which trends in biomass and recruitment are informed simultaneously by catch, multiple abundance indices, and composition data, with the latter carrying substantial influence over selectivity and year-class interpretation. The use of composition data at this level also means that weighting, effective sample size, and selectivity specification become major determinants of fit and inference (Francis, 2011).

7.1 Notation
Let s index stock, f fishery fleet, i abundance index, a age, l length bin, and y year. Let A denote the plus group age. The main state variable is numbers at age, N_{s,a,y}, at the start of year y.
The biological and fishery quantities used below are:

M_{s,a}: natural mortality;
S^{F}_{f,s,a,y}: fishery selectivity;
S^{I}_{i,s,a,y}: survey or index selectivity;
w^{\mathrm{pop}}_{s,a,y}, w^{\mathrm{catch}}_{f,s,a,y}, and w^{I}_{i,s,a,y}: population, catch, and index weights at age;
m_{s,a}: maturity at age;
q_i: catchability for abundance index i.

7.5 Abundance Indices
For abundance index i, the predicted index is a catchability-scaled vulnerable biomass or abundance quantity:

\begin{aligned}
I^{\mathrm{pred}}_{i,y}
&= q_i \sum_s \sum_a
N_{s,a,y}\exp(-\lambda_i Z_{s,a,y}) \\
&\quad \times S^{I}_{i,s,a,y} \, w^{I}_{i,s,a,y}.
\end{aligned}

where \lambda_i places the survey or CPUE observation within the year. This expression is schematic because some indices are closer to numbers-at-age and others to biomass, but it captures the model logic used across the SC13 index components.

7.8 Objective Function
The full estimation criterion combines data likelihoods, priors, and smoothing penalties:

\mathcal{L} =
\ell_{\mathrm{catch}}
+ \ell_{\mathrm{index}}
+ \ell_{\mathrm{age}}
+ \ell_{\mathrm{len}}
+ \ell_{\mathrm{priors}}
+ \ell_{\mathrm{sel}}.

The final term, \ell_{\mathrm{sel}}, is especially important in SC13 because the model includes extensive penalties on fishery and survey selectivity trajectories to regularize the time-varying non-parametric selectivity schedules.
